  "prompt": "What are the properties of orthoboric acid?",
  "response": "Orthoboric acid, also known simply as boric acid, is a weak acid with the chemical formula H3BO3. Here are some of its key properties:\n\n1. **Physical Properties**:\n   - **Appearance**: It typically appears as a white, crystalline powder or as colorless, odorless crystals.\n   - **Solubility**: It is sparingly soluble in cold water, but its solubility increases with temperature. It is also soluble in alcohol.\n   - **Melting Point**: It has a melting point of about 170.9\u00b0C (340\u00b0F), at which point it loses water and converts to metaboric acid (HBO2).\n   - **Density**: The density of boric acid is approximately 1.435 g/cm\u00b3.\n\n2. **Chemical Properties**:\n   - **Acidity**: Boric acid is a weak acid, and in water, it acts as a Lewis acid, accepting an OH\u207b ion from water to form B(OH)\u2084\u207b and H\u2083O\u207a.\n   - **Reactivity**: It reacts with alcohols to form borate esters. It also forms complexes with various compounds, including sugars and polyols.\n   - **Thermal Decomposition**: When heated above its melting point, boric acid dehydrates to form metaboric acid (HBO2), and further heating leads to the formation of tetraboric acid (H2B4O7) and eventually boron trioxide (B2O3).\n\n3. **Uses**:\n   - **Industrial Applications**: It is used in the manufacture of glass, ceramics, and enamels. It is also used as a fire retardant and in the production of boron compounds.\n   - **Pharmaceutical and Medicinal Uses**: Boric acid has antiseptic, antifungal, and antiviral properties, making it useful in medicinal applications, including eye washes and as a treatment for certain infections.\n   - **Agricultural Use**: It is used as a micronutrient fertilizer to correct boron deficiencies in plants.\n\n4. **Safety and Toxicity**:\n   - Boric acid is considered toxic if ingested in large amounts and can be harmful to the reproductive and developmental systems. It should be handled with care, and ingestion should be avoided.\n\nThese properties make boric acid a versatile compound with a wide range of applications across different industries.",
